# Practical 2 – Linux Commands (Information & File Management)

## AIM
To study and execute basic Linux commands for information and file management.

## INFORMATION COMMANDS
date          – display system date and time  
who           – show logged-in users  
pwd           – print current working directory  
cal 2025      – show calendar of year 2025  
wc file.txt   – show line, word and character count of a file  

## FILE MANAGEMENT COMMANDS
cat file.txt                 – display contents of a file  
cp file1 file2               – copy file1 to file2  
mv old new                   – rename or move a file  
rm file.txt                  – remove a file  
cmp f1 f2                    – compare two files byte by byte  
diff f1 f2                   – show line differences between files  
comm f1 f2                   – compare two sorted files line by line  
find . -name "*.c"           – find files with .c extension  
grep "word" file.txt         – search for "word" in file  
awk '{print $1}' file.txt    – print first column of each line  

## RESULT
Basic information and file management commands were executed
successfully in Linux.
